data.answer: The number 173 is prime according to our test from class. According to the test, we must check if any of the primes less than or equal to √173 can divide 173. Since the square of 13 is less than or equal to 173 and the square of 17 is greater than 173, √173 must be between 13 and 17. This means we can stop testing at 13. We checked to see if any of the primes up to that point divide 173 evenly. None of them divided 173, as evidenced by the list of quotients and remainders below. Thus, 173 is prime! Our work for testing potential prime divisors is shown below.
data.quotients_and_remainders: 173 \div 2 = 86 \text{ remainder } 1 \\ 173 \div 3 = 57 \text{ remainder } 2 \\ 173 \div 5 = 34 \text{ remainder } 3 \\ 173 \div 7 = 24 \text{ remainder } 5 \\ 173 \div 11 = 15 \text{ remainder } 8 \\ 173 \div 13 = 13 \text{ remainder } 4 \\
